.TH DMESG 8
.SH NAME
dmesg \- display kernel diagnostic messages
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dmesg
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dmesg
reads the kernel message buffer from
.B /dev/kmsg
and prints all messages to standard output.
This is the ELKS kernel ring buffer, which contains messages from
device drivers, the memory manager, the process scheduler, and other
kernel subsystems.
.PP
Typical uses include diagnosing boot-time hardware problems,
verifying device driver attachment, and checking for kernel errors
after a system event.
.PP
.B dmesg
reads until end-of-file on
.BR /dev/kmsg .
The kernel message buffer is a circular ring buffer.
When full, the oldest messages are silently discarded.
On ELKS the buffer is 2048 bytes, so on a busy system
.B dmesg
may not show messages from early boot.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Messages were read successfully.
.TP
.B 1
.B /dev/kmsg
could not be opened.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /dev/kmsg
Kernel message device.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR syslog (8).
